\f2\b\fs30 \cf2 1. Data Integrity and Accuracy
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Relational databases use structured schemas with defined data types and constraints (like primary keys, foreign keys, and unique constraints). This ensures data integrity and accuracy, preventing issues such as duplicate entries and orphan records.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 2. Ease of Use and SQL
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
The relational model uses Structured Query Language (SQL), a powerful and standardized language for querying and manipulating data. SQL\'92s widespread use and standardized syntax make it easier for developers and analysts to work with relational databases.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 3. Relationships and Joins
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Relational databases can efficiently handle complex queries involving multiple tables through joins. This capability allows for sophisticated data retrieval and reporting by linking related data across different tables.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 4. Scalability and Performance
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Modern relational databases are designed to handle large volumes of data and high transaction loads. Techniques like indexing, query optimization, and partitioning help maintain performance as the database scales.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 5. Data Consistency
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
The ACID (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) properties of relational databases ensure that transactions are processed reliably. This guarantees that data remains consistent and that concurrent transactions do not interfere with each other.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 6. Security
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Relational databases offer robust security features, including user authentication, role-based access control, and data encryption. These features help protect sensitive data and comply with regulatory requirements.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 7. Data Redundancy and Normalization
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Normalization is a process in relational databases that reduces data redundancy and ensures data dependencies are logical. This improves data integrity and reduces the storage required for the database.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 8. Backup and Recovery
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Relational databases provide comprehensive backup and recovery mechanisms. These features ensure data can be restored in case of hardware failures, software issues, or other disasters.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 9. Support for Transactions
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Relational databases support transactions, which are sequences of operations performed as a single logical unit of work. Transactions help ensure that either all operations are completed successfully or none are, preserving data integrity.\
\

\f2\b\fs30 10. Mature Ecosystem and Tools
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
There is a mature ecosystem of tools and software that support relational databases, including database management systems (DBMS), development environments, and performance monitoring tools. This ecosystem facilitates database administration, development, and optimization.\
\

